// Growing in the Spirit — Grace Daily devotional plan content
// Source: Bao's book "Growing in the Spirit" (faithdailywalk.com). Scripture: KJV (public domain).
// title, scripture, walk, prayer, oneThing, reflect = exact book text, untouched (Tiff-blessed).
// Anchor verse: Galatians 5:22-23 / Galatians 5:25 (KJV). Four-week arc: Life in the Spirit / Love Joy and Peace / Longsuffering Gentleness and Goodness / Meekness Temperance and the Spirit-Led Life.

const PLAN_SPIRIT = [
  {
    day: 1,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Life in the Spirit",
    title: "Born of the Spirit",
    ref: "John 3:6",
    scripture: "That which is born of the flesh is flesh; and that which is born of the Spirit is spirit.",
    walk: `Friend, we begin our journey into growing in the Spirit at the very beginning, with the new birth, because all spiritual growth flows from a spiritual birth. Speaking to Nicodemus by night, Jesus said, *That which is born of the flesh is flesh; and that which is born of the Spirit is spirit.* He was teaching that there are two kinds of birth, two kinds of life. There is the natural birth, by which we enter physical life, born of the flesh. And there is a second birth, a spiritual birth, by which we enter spiritual life, born of the Spirit. And without this second birth, Jesus said, no one can see the kingdom of God.

Consider what Jesus is telling us, friend, for it is foundational to everything else in this book. *That which is born of the flesh is flesh.* By our natural birth, we receive natural life, the life of the flesh. But the flesh, in its fallen state, cannot produce spiritual fruit. No matter how hard the flesh tries, it remains flesh; it cannot lift itself into the realm of the Spirit. This is why mere self-improvement can never produce true Christian growth. The flesh, however refined and disciplined, is still only flesh, and it cannot bring forth the fruit of the Spirit. Something more is needed: a new birth.

And that is exactly what Jesus offers: *that which is born of the Spirit is spirit.* By the new birth, the spiritual birth, we receive a new kind of life altogether, spiritual life, the very life of the Spirit within us. When we trust in Christ, the Holy Spirit comes to dwell in us and makes us new, gives us a new nature, a new heart, a new capacity for spiritual life that we did not have before. We are born again, born of the Spirit, and now there is within us a new life from which the fruit of the Spirit can grow. The growth this book is about is the growth of this new, Spirit-born life.

This is why we must begin here, friend. The fruit of the Spirit can only grow from a life that has been born of the Spirit. You cannot grow spiritual fruit from natural soil. The flesh cannot produce it. So the first and most fundamental question is not, *how hard am I trying?* but, *have I been born of the Spirit?* Have you come to Christ, trusted in Him, and received the Holy Spirit who makes all things new? For it is only from this new birth, this new life of the Spirit within you, that the fruit we will explore over these thirty days can grow.

So as we begin, friend, give thanks for the new birth if you have received it, and rest in the truth that the same Spirit who gave you new life is the Spirit who will grow His fruit in you. You are not trying to produce spiritual fruit from the dead soil of the flesh; you have been born of the Spirit, and the living Spirit within you is the source of all the growth to come. And if you have never been born of the Spirit, friend, do not pass by this first day lightly. Come to Christ. Be born again. Receive the Spirit who makes all things new. For all true growth begins here, with that which is born of the Spirit.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You that by Your Spirit I have been born again, given new life, a new nature, a new capacity for spiritual growth that the flesh could never produce. Help me to rest in the truth that the same Spirit who gave me new life will grow His fruit in me. I cannot produce spiritual fruit from the soil of the flesh, but the living Spirit within me is the source of all growth. Grow Your life in me, Lord. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, give thanks for the new birth, and remind yourself that all your growth flows from the Spirit's life within you, not from the flesh's effort. Rest in the truth: *I have been born of the Spirit, and He will grow His fruit in me.*`,
    reflect: `Why can the flesh, no matter how hard it tries, never produce the fruit of the Spirit? How does it change your approach to growth to know that the fruit grows from a new life "born of the Spirit"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 2,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Life in the Spirit",
    title: "The Spirit Dwells in You",
    ref: "Romans 8:9",
    scripture: "But ye are not in the flesh, but in the Spirit, if so be that the Spirit of God dwell in you. Now if any man have not the Spirit of Christ, he is none of his.",
    walk: `Friend, having been born of the Spirit, we now learn a wonderful truth about where the Spirit is: He dwells in us. *Ye are not in the flesh, but in the Spirit, if so be that the Spirit of God dwell in you.* Paul tells the believers that the Spirit of God dwells in them, lives in them, has taken up residence within them. This is one of the most staggering truths of the Christian life, and the very engine of all our spiritual growth. The Holy Spirit, the third Person of the Trinity, God Himself, dwells within every believer.

Consider the wonder of this, friend. We might have expected that God's Spirit would remain distant, that He would work upon us from the outside, helping us along while remaining apart from us. But the truth of the gospel is far more intimate. The Spirit of God dwells *in* us. He does not merely visit; He resides. He has made our very hearts His home. The same Spirit who hovered over the waters at creation, who empowered the prophets, who raised Christ from the dead, that Spirit lives within you if you belong to Christ. You are, as Paul says elsewhere, a temple of the Holy Spirit. God dwells in you.

And see how Paul connects this to our identity: *Now if any man have not the Spirit of Christ, he is none of his.* The presence of the indwelling Spirit is the mark of belonging to Christ. Every true believer has the Spirit of Christ dwelling in them; it is not an advanced experience reserved for a special few, but the common possession of all who belong to Jesus. If you are Christ's, the Spirit dwells in you. This means the source of spiritual growth is not somewhere far off that you must somehow reach; it is already within you. The Spirit who grows the fruit is already at home in your heart.

What confidence this gives for the growth we are pursuing, friend. We are not trying to grow spiritual fruit by drawing on resources we do not have, straining toward a Spirit who is distant. The Spirit who produces the fruit lives within us. The power for love, joy, peace, and all the rest is not external to us but internal, dwelling in our very hearts. Our task in growing, then, is not to summon the Spirit from afar, but to yield to the Spirit who is already within, to cooperate with His work, to let Him have His way in us. The fruit grows from the inside out, from the Spirit who dwells within.

So live today, friend, in the awareness of the indwelling Spirit. The God who grows all the fruit we long for is not distant from you; He lives within you. When you long to be more loving, remember that the Spirit of love dwells in you. When you long for joy or peace or patience, remember that the Spirit who produces them is already at home in your heart. You are not alone in your pursuit of growth, and you are not relying on your own resources. The Spirit of God dwells in you, and He is the living source of all the fruit to come. Yield to Him, friend, cooperate with Him, and let the One who dwells within grow His life in you.`,
    prayer: `Lord, what a wonder that Your Spirit dwells in me, that You have made my very heart Your home. Help me to live in awareness of Your indwelling presence, knowing that the source of all the fruit I long for is not distant but within me. Teach me to yield to Your Spirit, to cooperate with His work, and to let the One who dwells in me grow His life and fruit in my heart. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, live in awareness of the Spirit dwelling within you. When you long for more love, joy, or patience, remind yourself: *The Spirit who produces these lives in me*, and turn to Him within rather than straining by your own effort.`,
    reflect: `How does it change your pursuit of growth to know that the Spirit who produces the fruit already dwells within you? What would it look like to "yield to" the indwelling Spirit rather than relying on your own resources?`,
  },
  {
    day: 3,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Life in the Spirit",
    title: "Led by the Spirit",
    ref: "Romans 8:14",
    scripture: "For as many as are led by the Spirit of God, they are the sons of God.",
    walk: `Friend, Paul here describes a beautiful mark of those who belong to God: they are *led by the Spirit.* *For as many as are led by the Spirit of God, they are the sons of God.* The children of God are not those who merely have the Spirit dwelling in them, but those who are *led* by Him, who follow His guidance, who yield to His direction, who walk where He leads. And learning to be led by the Spirit is essential to growing in the Spirit, for the fruit grows in those who follow His lead.

Consider what it means to be led by the Spirit. To be led is to follow, to yield to another's direction, to go where you are guided rather than charging ahead on your own. The Spirit of God leads the children of God, prompting them toward what is good, restraining them from what is harmful, guiding them in the way they should go, drawing them toward Christ and away from sin. And those who are God's children are marked by this: they follow His leading. They have learned to be sensitive to His promptings, to yield to His guidance, to let Him direct their steps rather than insisting on their own way.

Notice that being led by the Spirit is presented as the evidence of sonship: *they are the sons of God.* This does not mean we earn our sonship by being led; rather, those who are truly God's children show it by their responsiveness to the Spirit's leading. A child resembles his father and follows his father's guidance; the children of God resemble their Father and follow the leading of His Spirit. So the question of whether we are growing in the Spirit is closely tied to whether we are being led by the Spirit, whether we are sensitive and responsive to His promptings, or whether we are charging ahead on our own, ignoring His gentle direction.

How, then, do we follow the Spirit's leading, friend? It begins with cultivating sensitivity to His promptings. The Spirit leads us primarily through the Word of God, illuminating its truth and applying it to our hearts. He leads us through an inner prompting toward righteousness and away from sin, a quiet conviction, a gentle nudge, a growing sense of what pleases God. And to be led by Him, we must learn to pay attention, to listen, to be responsive rather than resistant, to yield to His direction the moment we sense it rather than pushing on in our own way. The more we yield to His leading, the more clearly we learn to discern it, and the more we grow.

So learn to be led by the Spirit, friend. Cultivate a heart that listens for His promptings and yields to His guidance. When you sense Him drawing you toward what is good, follow. When you sense Him restraining you from what is harmful, stop. When His Word convicts you or directs you, obey. This responsive, yielded following is the path of growth, for the fruit of the Spirit grows in those who walk where the Spirit leads. You are a child of God, friend, marked by the leading of His Spirit. So follow His lead, day by day, and you will grow into the likeness of your Father.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You have shown me that Your children are those who are led by Your Spirit. Cultivate in me a heart that is sensitive to Your promptings and responsive to Your guidance. Help me to follow when You draw me toward good, to stop when You restrain me from harm, and to obey when Your Word directs me. Teach me to be led by Your Spirit, day by day, and to grow into the likeness of my Father. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, pay attention to the Spirit's promptings, His nudges toward good, His restraints from harm, His convictions through the Word, and deliberately yield to His leading the moment you sense it, rather than charging ahead on your own.`,
    reflect: `What does it mean, practically, to be "led by the Spirit"? Are you cultivating a heart that listens for and yields to His promptings, or charging ahead on your own way?`,
  },
  {
    day: 4,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Life in the Spirit",
    title: "Walk in the Spirit",
    ref: "Galatians 5:16",
    scripture: "This I say then, Walk in the Spirit, and ye shall not fulfil the lust of the flesh.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul gives us the great practical command of the Spirit-led life, the command that frames our whole anchor passage: *Walk in the Spirit, and ye shall not fulfil the lust of the flesh.* This image of *walking* in the Spirit is one of the most helpful pictures in all of Scripture for how we grow. And the promise attached to it is wonderful: as we walk in the Spirit, we will not fulfill the cravings of the flesh. The way to overcome the flesh is not mainly by fighting it directly, but by walking in the Spirit.

Consider the image of *walking.* Walking is not a single dramatic act but a steady, ongoing, step-by-step process. You do not walk somewhere all at once; you walk one step at a time, continually, in a steady progression toward your destination. And so the Spirit-led life is a walk, a steady, day-by-day, step-by-step following of the Spirit, a continual yielding to Him and drawing of life from Him. Growing in the Spirit is not about occasional dramatic experiences; it is about a steady walk, taking one Spirit-led step after another, day in and day out. The fruit grows through this faithful, ongoing walk.

And see the wonderful promise attached to the command: *and ye shall not fulfil the lust of the flesh.* Paul does not say, *fight the flesh as hard as you can, and you will overcome it.* He says, *walk in the Spirit, and ye shall not fulfil the lust of the flesh.* The way to overcome the cravings of the flesh is not primarily by direct combat with them, but by walking in the Spirit. When we are walking in the Spirit, yielding to Him, drawing our life from Him, following His lead, the flesh loses its power over us, almost as a byproduct. We do not fulfill the lust of the flesh, not because we have fought it into submission, but because we are walking in the Spirit, and the two cannot occupy the same step.

This is a liberating truth, friend, for those who have wearied themselves fighting the flesh directly. So often we focus all our energy on battling our sins, white-knuckling our way against temptation, and we find ourselves exhausted and defeated. But Paul redirects our focus. He says, walk in the Spirit, and the flesh will not have its way. Fill your life with the positive pursuit of the Spirit, yielding to Him, walking with Him, drawing life from Him, and you will find the flesh losing its grip, not because you fought it directly, but because you were walking in the Spirit. The best defense against the flesh is a Spirit-filled walk.

So make this your aim, friend: to walk in the Spirit. Not occasionally, not dramatically, but steadily, step by step, day by day. Begin each day yielding to the Spirit. Throughout the day, keep in step with Him, following His lead, drawing your life from Him, returning to Him whenever you drift. This steady walk is the path of growth, and it carries a promise: as you walk in the Spirit, you will not fulfill the lust of the flesh. So do not exhaust yourself merely fighting your sins; walk in the Spirit, and watch the flesh lose its grip as the fruit of the Spirit grows in its place.`,
    prayer: `Lord, teach me to walk in the Spirit, steadily, day by day, step by step. I have wearied myself fighting the flesh directly; help me instead to fill my life with the positive pursuit of the Spirit, yielding to Him and drawing my life from Him. Thank You for the promise that as I walk in the Spirit, I will not fulfill the lust of the flesh. Help me to keep in step with You today, and every day. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, instead of focusing your energy on fighting a particular sin directly, focus on "walking in the Spirit", yielding to Him, keeping in step with Him throughout the day, and trust the promise that you will then "not fulfil the lust of the flesh."`,
    reflect: `What is the difference between fighting the flesh directly and "walking in the Spirit"? How might filling your life with the positive pursuit of the Spirit cause the flesh to lose its grip?`,
  },
  {
    day: 5,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Life in the Spirit",
    title: "The Flesh Against the Spirit",
    ref: "Galatians 5:17",
    scripture: "For the flesh lusteth against the Spirit, and the Spirit against the flesh: and these are contrary the one to the other: so that ye cannot do the things that ye would.",
    walk: `Friend, Paul here describes honestly the inner conflict that every growing believer experiences: *the flesh lusteth against the Spirit, and the Spirit against the flesh: and these are contrary the one to the other.* Within the Christian there are two opposing principles, the flesh and the Spirit, and they are at war with one another. Understanding this conflict is essential to growing in the Spirit, because it explains the struggle we feel and points us toward the path of victory.

Consider what Paul is describing. The believer has been born of the Spirit and has the Spirit dwelling within. But the flesh, the old fallen nature with its sinful cravings, has not yet been fully eradicated; it remains, and it wars against the Spirit. So there are two principles within us, pulling in opposite directions. The Spirit draws us toward God, toward holiness, toward the fruit of love and joy and peace. The flesh draws us toward sin, toward self, toward the works of the flesh. And these two are *contrary the one to the other*, locked in conflict, each opposing the other within us.

This explains the struggle we feel, friend, and it is actually a comfort to understand it. Sometimes new believers, or those earnestly seeking to grow, are discouraged to discover this inner war. They expected that once they came to Christ, the struggle with sin would simply vanish, and when it does not, they wonder if something is wrong with them. But Paul tells us that this conflict is normal, even a sign of spiritual life. The very fact that you feel the war between the flesh and the Spirit shows that the Spirit is present and active within you, opposing the flesh. The unbeliever feels no such war; they simply follow the flesh. But the believer feels the conflict precisely because the Spirit is now within, contending against the flesh.

And see the honest acknowledgment Paul makes: *so that ye cannot do the things that ye would.* Because of this conflict, we often find ourselves unable to do the good we genuinely want to do. We desire to love, but the flesh stirs up selfishness. We desire to be patient, but the flesh stirs up irritation. The presence of the flesh frustrates our best intentions, so that we cannot simply do the good we would. This is the experience of every honest believer, and Paul names it plainly. We are not yet what we will be; the flesh still wars against the Spirit, frustrating our growth.

But do not despair at this conflict, friend, for the very passage that names it also points to the path of victory. The answer to the war between the flesh and the Spirit is not to fight the flesh in our own strength, which only leads to defeat, but to walk in the Spirit, as we saw yesterday. The Spirit is stronger than the flesh, and as we yield to Him and walk in Him, He gains the victory in us. The conflict is real, but the Spirit is mightier than the flesh, and the outcome is not in doubt for those who walk in Him. So do not be discouraged by the inner war, friend. It is the mark of spiritual life. And take heart: the Spirit who wars against your flesh is mightier than it, and as you walk in Him, He will give you the victory.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for honestly naming the war I feel within, between the flesh and the Spirit. Help me to see that this conflict is not a sign that something is wrong, but a mark of the Spirit's presence and life within me. When the flesh frustrates the good I want to do, keep me from despair. Remind me that Your Spirit is mightier than my flesh, and as I walk in Him, You will give me the victory. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when you feel the inner war between flesh and Spirit, do not be discouraged by it. Recognize it as a mark of the Spirit's life in you, and respond not by fighting the flesh in your own strength, but by yielding afresh to the Spirit who is mightier.`,
    reflect: `Have you been discouraged by the inner conflict between flesh and Spirit? How does it help to know this war is a mark of spiritual life, and that the Spirit is mightier than the flesh?`,
  },
  {
    day: 6,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Life in the Spirit",
    title: "Sowing to the Spirit",
    ref: "Galatians 6:8",
    scripture: "For he that soweth to his flesh shall of the flesh reap corruption; but he that soweth to the Spirit shall of the Spirit reap life everlasting.",
    walk: `Friend, Paul here uses the familiar image of sowing and reaping to teach us a crucial principle about spiritual growth: *he that soweth to the Spirit shall of the Spirit reap life everlasting.* What we sow, we reap. And in the spiritual life, we are always sowing, either to the flesh or to the Spirit, and we will reap accordingly. This principle puts a measure of our growth back into our own hands, not in the sense of earning it, but in the sense that we choose, by our daily choices, what we are cultivating.

Consider the principle of sowing and reaping. Every farmer knows it: you reap what you sow. Sow wheat, and you reap wheat. Sow weeds, and you reap weeds. And the harvest is always greater than the seed; a little seed sown produces a large crop. Paul applies this to the spiritual life. We are constantly sowing, by our choices, our habits, our thoughts, what we feed our minds, how we spend our time, what we yield to. And we are sowing either to the flesh or to the Spirit. The choices that indulge and feed the flesh are sowing to the flesh. The choices that nurture and feed our spiritual life are sowing to the Spirit. And we will reap a harvest from whichever we sow to.

See the two harvests Paul describes. *He that soweth to his flesh shall of the flesh reap corruption.* When we sow to the flesh, indulging its cravings, feeding its appetites, yielding to its pulls, we reap corruption, decay, the rotting of our spiritual life, and ultimately death. The flesh, fed and cultivated, produces a harvest of ruin. But *he that soweth to the Spirit shall of the Spirit reap life everlasting.* When we sow to the Spirit, nurturing our spiritual life, feeding on God's Word, yielding to the Spirit's promptings, cultivating the things of God, we reap life, the abundant, growing, everlasting life of the Spirit. The fruit of the Spirit is, in this sense, a harvest we reap from sowing to the Spirit.

This teaches us that our daily choices matter enormously for our growth, friend. We sometimes imagine that spiritual growth happens automatically, or that our small daily choices are insignificant. But Paul says we are always sowing, and we will reap what we sow. The hours we spend feeding our minds on what is good or what is corrupt, the habits we cultivate or neglect, the promptings of the Spirit we heed or ignore, all of these are seeds sown, and they will produce a harvest. The believer who consistently sows to the Spirit, day after day, in small faithful choices, will reap a rich harvest of spiritual fruit. The one who carelessly sows to the flesh will reap corruption.

So sow to the Spirit, friend, in the daily choices that make up your life. Feed your mind on God's Word rather than on what corrupts. Cultivate habits of prayer and worship and fellowship that nurture your spiritual life. Yield to the Spirit's promptings rather than the flesh's pulls. Spend your time and attention on the things of God. These are seeds sown to the Spirit, and from them you will reap a harvest of life and fruit. Do not be deceived; you will reap what you sow. So sow generously to the Spirit, day by day, and in due season you will reap the abundant fruit of a Spirit-led life.`,
    prayer: `Lord, help me to remember that I am always sowing, by my daily choices, either to the flesh or to the Spirit, and that I will reap what I sow. Give me the wisdom and discipline to sow to the Spirit, to feed my mind on Your Word, to cultivate habits that nurture my spiritual life, and to yield to Your promptings. Let me sow generously to the Spirit, that I might reap a rich harvest of life and fruit. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, examine what you are "sowing" in your daily choices, what you feed your mind on, how you spend your time, what you yield to. Choose one specific way to "sow to the Spirit" rather than to the flesh.`,
    reflect: `What are you sowing in your daily choices, to the flesh or to the Spirit? What harvest are those seeds likely to produce, and what is one way you could sow more deliberately to the Spirit?`,
  },
  {
    day: 7,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Life in the Spirit",
    title: "Filled with the Spirit",
    ref: "Ephesians 5:18",
    scripture: "And be not drunk with wine, wherein is excess; but be filled with the Spirit.",
    walk: `Friend, we close this first week on life in the Spirit with a command that points to the fullness of the Spirit-led life: *be filled with the Spirit.* Paul sets it in contrast to drunkenness: *be not drunk with wine, wherein is excess; but be filled with the Spirit.* The comparison is instructive. Just as wine, when someone is drunk with it, fills and controls and influences them, so we are to be filled with the Spirit, allowing Him to fill and control and influence our whole lives. And this fullness of the Spirit is the soil in which the richest fruit grows.

Consider the contrast Paul draws. A person who is drunk with wine is filled and controlled by it; the wine influences their words, their actions, their whole demeanor. Paul does not commend this, of course; he warns against it. But he uses it as a contrast to make a point about being filled with the Spirit. Just as wine fills and controls the drunkard, so the Spirit is to fill and control the believer, influencing our words, our actions, our whole demeanor, so that we are governed by Him rather than by the flesh or by anything else. To be filled with the Spirit is to be so yielded to Him that He permeates and directs the whole of our lives.

Notice that *be filled with the Spirit* is a command, which tells us something important. The fullness of the Spirit is not merely something that happens to passive believers; it is something we are commanded to pursue, to seek, to yield to. This does not mean we earn the Spirit's fullness by our effort, but that we have a responsibility to yield ourselves to Him, to make room for Him, to seek to be filled rather than resisting or quenching Him. And the verb tense in the original suggests an ongoing, continual filling, not a one-time event but a repeated, daily yielding to be filled with the Spirit again and again. We are to keep on being filled.

How are we filled with the Spirit, friend? Not by some complicated technique, but by yielding ourselves wholly to Him, making room for Him, removing the obstacles of unconfessed sin and self-will, and asking Him to fill us. As we surrender more and more of ourselves to the Spirit, He fills more and more of us. As we confess and turn from sin, we remove the hindrances to His filling. As we feed on God's Word and spend time in prayer and worship, we open ourselves to His fullness. The Spirit-filled life is a life of ongoing surrender, of continually yielding ourselves to the Spirit and asking Him to fill us afresh.

And see the result, for it is the very theme of this book. The believer who is filled with the Spirit is the believer in whom the fruit of the Spirit grows most richly. When the Spirit fills and controls our lives, His fruit, love, joy, peace, and all the rest, flows out of us abundantly, because we are full of Him. The fullness of the Spirit and the fruit of the Spirit go together. So seek to be filled with the Spirit, friend. Yield yourself wholly to Him. Remove the obstacles of sin and self-will. Make room for Him in your life. And keep on being filled, day by day, that the fruit of the Spirit might grow richly in a life that is full of Him.`,
    prayer: `Lord, I want to be filled with Your Spirit, so yielded to You that You fill and control and influence my whole life. Show me the obstacles of unconfessed sin and self-will that hinder Your filling, and help me to remove them. Teach me to make room for You, to surrender myself wholly to You, and to keep on being filled, day by day. Let Your fruit grow richly in a life that is full of You. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, seek to "be filled with the Spirit" by yielding yourself wholly to Him. Remove one obstacle, a known sin or area of self-will, and ask the Spirit to fill that space, surrendering it to His control.`,
    reflect: `What does it mean to be "filled with the Spirit," so yielded to Him that He fills and controls your life? What obstacles of sin or self-will might be hindering His filling, and how might you make more room for Him?`,
  },
  {
    day: 8,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "Love, Joy, and Peace",
    title: "Love Shed Abroad in Our Hearts",
    ref: "Romans 5:5",
    scripture: "And hope maketh not ashamed; because the love of God is shed abroad in our hearts by the Holy Ghost which is given unto us.",
    walk: `Friend, this week we begin to take up the fruit of the Spirit itself, and we start where Paul starts, with love, the first and greatest of the fruit. And our first verse shows us exactly how this love comes to be in us: *the love of God is shed abroad in our hearts by the Holy Ghost which is given unto us.* Love is not something we manufacture by trying harder; it is shed abroad in our hearts by the Holy Spirit. The very love we are called to show is poured into us by the Spirit who lives within us.

Consider that beautiful phrase, *shed abroad.* The word pictures a lavish pouring out, a flooding, an abundant outpouring of love into our hearts. The love of God is not given to us in a trickle, carefully measured out; it is shed abroad, poured out lavishly, flooding our hearts by the Holy Spirit. This is first of all the love of God *for us*, His vast, lavish love poured into our hearts so that we know ourselves loved. The Spirit floods our hearts with the assurance of God's love, so that we are rooted and grounded in being loved by God. And out of that experience of being loved flows our love for others.

This is the key to growing in love, friend, and it sets the pattern for all the fruit. We cannot manufacture love by sheer willpower. We cannot squeeze love out of an empty heart. Love must first be poured into us before it can flow out of us. And that is exactly what the Spirit does: He sheds abroad the love of God in our hearts. As we experience the lavish love of God poured into us by the Spirit, our hearts are filled with love, and that love begins to overflow toward others. We love because we are first loved, and the love we are first loved with is shed abroad in our hearts by the Spirit.

So the way to grow in love is not first to strive harder to love, but to receive more deeply the love that the Spirit sheds abroad in our hearts. When our hearts are full of the assurance of God's lavish love for us, love for others flows naturally. But when we feel unloved, empty, running on a love-deficit, we have little love to give. So the first step in growing in love is to let the Spirit flood your heart afresh with the love of God for you, to receive deeply that you are loved, lavishly, completely, by God, and then to let that love overflow.

So open your heart to the love the Spirit sheds abroad, friend. When you long to be more loving, do not first strain to produce love by effort. Instead, ask the Spirit to flood your heart afresh with the love of God for you. Meditate on how lavishly you are loved, how Christ died for you, how the Father delights in you. Let the Spirit shed this love abroad in your heart. And as your heart fills with the assurance of God's love, you will find love for others beginning to overflow, not manufactured by effort, but grown by the Spirit, who sheds abroad the love of God in the hearts of those who are His.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You that You do not ask me to manufacture love by my own effort, but shed abroad Your love in my heart by the Holy Spirit. Flood my heart afresh today with the assurance of Your lavish love for me. Help me to receive deeply that I am loved, completely and forever, by You. And let that love overflow from me toward others, grown by Your Spirit, not squeezed out by my striving. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, before trying to love others by effort, ask the Spirit to "shed abroad" the love of God in your heart. Meditate on how lavishly you are loved by God, and let that fullness overflow toward someone.`,
    reflect: `Why can't love be manufactured by willpower? How does receiving the love of God "shed abroad in our hearts" by the Spirit become the source from which love for others overflows?`,
  },
  {
    day: 9,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "Love, Joy, and Peace",
    title: "Love One Another",
    ref: "1 John 4:7",
    scripture: "Beloved, let us love one another: for love is of God; and every one that loveth is born of God, and knoweth God.",
    walk: `Friend, having seen that love is poured into us by the Spirit, we now hear the call to let that love flow out: *Beloved, let us love one another: for love is of God.* John calls us to love one another, and he grounds this call in a profound truth: *love is of God.* The love we are called to show originates in God, flows from God, and is, in fact, evidence that we know God. To love is to show that we have been born of God and have come to know Him, for God is the source of all true love.

Notice first the tender way John addresses his readers: *Beloved.* Before he calls them to love, he reminds them that they are loved. *Beloved, let us love one another.* This is the right order, the very order we saw yesterday. We are first beloved, loved by God, and out of being beloved we are called to love. John does not say, *love one another in order to become beloved.* He says, *Beloved,* you who are already loved, *let us love one another.* Our love for others flows out of our security in being loved by God. We love from a place of being beloved.

And see why John calls us to love: *for love is of God.* True love, John tells us, originates in God; it is of God, flowing from His very nature, for God Himself is love. This means that when we love one another with genuine love, we are participating in something that comes from God, expressing His own nature, doing what He does. Love is not merely a human sentiment; it is, at its truest, a divine thing, flowing from God into us and out through us to others. To love is to share in the very life and nature of God.

And John makes a striking claim about those who love: *every one that loveth is born of God, and knoweth God.* Genuine love is evidence of spiritual life. Those who truly love show that they have been born of God and have come to know Him. Why? Because, as John explains, love comes from God, and so the presence of real love in a person's life shows that God's life is in them. You cannot consistently love others with genuine, self-giving love unless God's love is at work in you. So love becomes a mark of the new birth, a sign that we have been born of God and know Him. Where God's love is truly received, love for others is the natural fruit.

So let us love one another, friend, not as an isolated duty grimly performed, but as the natural overflow of being loved by God and born of Him. When you find it hard to love a particular person, return first to the truth that you are beloved, loved by God, and ask Him to let His love flow through you to them. Remember that love is of God, that as you love, you are sharing in His very nature and doing what He does. And take encouragement that your love, however imperfect, is evidence that you have been born of God and know Him. Beloved, let us love one another, for love is of God, and the God who is love dwells in us by His Spirit, ready to love others through us.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me, as Your beloved, to love one another, for love is of God. Help me to love not as a grim duty, but as the natural overflow of being loved by You. When I find it hard to love someone, remind me that I am beloved, and let Your love flow through me to them. Thank You that as I love, I share in Your very nature. Let love be the fruit that shows I am born of You. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, choose one person who is hard for you to love, and ask God to let His love flow through you to them. Love them with a concrete act, remembering that as you do, you share in God's own nature.`,
    reflect: `How does being "beloved" by God enable you to "love one another"? What does it mean that genuine love is evidence that someone is "born of God, and knoweth God"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 10,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "Love, Joy, and Peace",
    title: "The Joy of the Lord",
    ref: "Nehemiah 8:10",
    scripture: "...neither be ye sorry; for the joy of the LORD is your strength.",
    walk: `Friend, we turn now to the second fruit of the Spirit, joy, and we begin with one of the most beloved statements about joy in all of Scripture: *the joy of the LORD is your strength.* These words were spoken to God's people as they wept, hearing the law read and convicted of how far they had fallen short. And the leaders comforted them, telling them not to be sorrowful, for the joy of the Lord was their strength. This teaches us something profound about the joy that is a fruit of the Spirit: it is a source of strength, and it is the Lord's own joy.

Notice first the nature of this joy: it is *the joy of the LORD.* This is not merely human happiness, not the fleeting good feeling that comes when circumstances are pleasant. It is the joy of the Lord, a joy that comes from God, that is rooted in Him, that flows from our relationship with Him. This is why it can be present even in hard circumstances, even, as in Nehemiah, in a moment of weeping and conviction. The joy of the Lord does not depend on our circumstances being easy; it depends on the Lord, who does not change. And because its source is the unchanging God, this joy can be steady and deep even when our outward circumstances give us little to be happy about.

And see what this joy does for us: *the joy of the LORD is your strength.* The joy of the Lord is not merely a pleasant feeling; it is a source of strength. There is power in joy. The joy of the Lord strengthens us, sustains us, gives us the energy and resilience to face difficulty, to keep going, to endure. A joyless faith is a weak faith, easily worn down; but the believer who has the joy of the Lord has a deep reservoir of strength to draw upon. When we are joyful in the Lord, we are strong; when we lose our joy, we grow weak. The joy of the Lord is your strength, a strength that the world, with its circumstance-dependent happiness, knows nothing about.

Consider the setting in which these words were spoken, friend, for it is instructive. God's people were weeping in sorrow and conviction. And the answer was not to wallow in that sorrow, but to find strength in the joy of the Lord. This does not mean we never grieve or mourn; there is a place for godly sorrow over sin. But it does mean that we are not to be overcome by sorrow, that even in our weeping we can find strength in the joy of the Lord, the joy that comes from being His, forgiven, loved, and secure in Him. The joy of the Lord lifts us out of the weakness of sorrow into the strength of rejoicing in Him.

So draw on the joy of the Lord for your strength today, friend. When you feel weak, weary, worn down, do not look first to your circumstances for a lift, for they may give you none. Look instead to the Lord, and let the joy of the Lord, the joy that flows from being His, become your strength. Rejoice in who He is, in what He has done, in your salvation, in your secure standing in Christ. Let this joy fill and strengthen you. For the joy of the Lord is your strength, a deep and steady strength rooted in the unchanging God, available to you even in your hardest and most sorrowful days. Rejoice in the Lord, friend, and be strong.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You that the joy of the Lord is my strength, a joy rooted not in my changing circumstances but in You, the unchanging God. When I feel weak and worn down, help me to draw not on my circumstances but on the joy that flows from being Yours, forgiven, loved, and secure in Christ. Let this joy fill and strengthen me, even on my hardest days. Rejoice my heart in You. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when you feel weak or weary, draw on "the joy of the LORD" for strength. Rather than looking to your circumstances, rejoice deliberately in who God is and what He has done in your salvation, and let that joy strengthen you.`,
    reflect: `How is "the joy of the LORD" different from circumstance-dependent happiness? How might drawing on this joy, rooted in the unchanging God, become a real source of strength in your weakness?`,
  },
  {
    day: 11,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "Love, Joy, and Peace",
    title: "Fulness of Joy in His Presence",
    ref: "Psalm 16:11",
    scripture: "Thou wilt shew me the path of life: in thy presence is fulness of joy; at thy right hand there are pleasures for evermore.",
    walk: `Friend, here David shows us where the truest and fullest joy is found: *in thy presence is fulness of joy.* Not in circumstances, not in possessions, not in achievements, but in the presence of God Himself is found the fullness of joy. And at God's right hand, David says, there are pleasures forevermore. This points us to the deep source of the joy that is a fruit of the Spirit: it is found in God's presence, in nearness to Him, in communion with Him.

Consider that phrase, *fulness of joy.* Not a little joy, not a partial joy, but the fullness of joy, joy complete and overflowing, joy that fills the heart to the brim. And where is this fullness found? *In thy presence.* The presence of God is the place of full joy. This is a profound truth that our hearts are slow to believe. We tend to seek our joy everywhere else, in pleasures and possessions and accomplishments, in the approval of others, in the satisfying of our desires. And these may give us moments of happiness, but never the fullness of joy. That fullness is found only in one place: in the presence of God. To be near to God, to commune with Him, to dwell in His presence, is to find the joy that nothing else can give.

And see the permanence of the pleasures David describes: *at thy right hand there are pleasures for evermore.* The pleasures of God's presence are not fleeting, like the pleasures of this world, which fade as soon as they are grasped. They are *for evermore*, eternal, unending, ever-fresh. The world's pleasures are temporary and leave us empty; God's pleasures are eternal and ever-satisfying. At God's right hand there is an inexhaustible fountain of joy and pleasure that never runs dry, never fades, never disappoints. This is what God offers to those who seek their joy in Him: not the fleeting pleasures of a moment, but pleasures forevermore.

This shows us where to seek joy if we want it to grow as a fruit of the Spirit, friend. So often we seek joy in everything but God, and we wonder why it eludes us or why it never lasts. But David points us to the true source: the presence of God. If we want the fullness of joy, we must seek it in nearness to God, in communion with Him, in dwelling in His presence through prayer, worship, and His Word. The joy that is a fruit of the Spirit grows as we draw near to God, for it is in His presence that fullness of joy is found. The closer we are to Him, the more our joy increases.

So seek your joy in God's presence today, friend, and seek it there above all else. When your joy runs thin, do not chase after the fleeting pleasures of the world, which can never fill you. Draw near to God instead. Spend time in His presence through prayer and worship. Open His Word and meet with Him there. Cultivate communion with the God in whose presence is fullness of joy. For the deepest, fullest, most lasting joy is not found in anything this world offers, but in nearness to God Himself. Draw near to Him, friend, and find in His presence the fullness of joy and the pleasures that are forevermore.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You have shown me that the fullness of joy is found in Your presence, and that at Your right hand are pleasures forevermore. Forgive me for seeking my joy everywhere but in You, in fleeting pleasures that never satisfy. Teach me to draw near to You, to cultivate communion with You, and to find in Your presence the fullness of joy that nothing else can give. Draw me close, Lord, and fill me with the joy of Your presence. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when your joy runs thin, seek it in God's presence rather than in fleeting pleasures. Draw near to Him through prayer, worship, or His Word, and look for the "fulness of joy" found in nearness to Him.`,
    reflect: `Where have you been seeking your joy, and has it satisfied? What would it look like to seek the "fulness of joy" found in God's presence, drawing near to Him as the true source of lasting joy?`,
  },
  {
    day: 12,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "Love, Joy, and Peace",
    title: "Joy Unspeakable",
    ref: "1 Peter 1:8",
    scripture: "Whom having not seen, ye love; in whom, though now ye see him not, yet believing, ye rejoice with joy unspeakable and full of glory.",
    walk: `Friend, Peter here describes a joy so great that words cannot contain it: *ye rejoice with joy unspeakable and full of glory.* This is the joy that the Spirit produces in those who love and believe in Christ, even though they have never seen Him with their eyes. It is a joy beyond words, *unspeakable*, and shot through with glory. And it is available to ordinary believers like us, who have not seen Christ but love Him and trust Him still.

Notice first who experiences this joy. Peter is writing to believers who, like us, had never seen Jesus with their physical eyes. *Whom having not seen, ye love; in whom, though now ye see him not, yet believing, ye rejoice.* This is remarkable. These believers loved a Savior they had never seen and rejoiced in One who was not visible to them, on the basis of faith. And so do we. We have not seen Christ, and yet we love Him. We do not see Him now, and yet, believing, we rejoice. This joy is not based on sight, on having Christ visibly present before us, but on faith, on loving and trusting the Savior we cannot see. It is the joy of faith.

And what a joy it is: *joy unspeakable and full of glory.* The word *unspeakable* means it cannot be fully expressed in words; it is beyond the power of language to capture. This is no small, ordinary gladness, but a joy so deep and so great that words fail before it. And it is *full of glory*, shot through with the glory of heaven, a foretaste of the joy of God's presence, carrying within it something of the radiance of glory itself. This is the joy that the Spirit can produce in the heart of a believer, a joy beyond words, full of glory, even in a world of trouble, even without seeing Christ face to face.

How is such a joy possible, friend, for those who have not seen? It is possible because it is a fruit of the Spirit, produced not by favorable circumstances but by the Spirit's work in the believing heart. When we love Christ and trust Him, the Spirit fills us with a joy that does not depend on seeing, a joy rooted in who Christ is and what He has done, a joy that anticipates the glory to come. This joy can coexist with trial and sorrow, for it does not depend on our circumstances but on our Savior. Peter's readers were facing real suffering, and yet they rejoiced with joy unspeakable, because their joy was in Christ, not in their circumstances.

So do not think that joy unspeakable is reserved for some special class of believers, friend, or that it requires seeing Christ visibly or having everything go well. It is the fruit of the Spirit in the heart of any believer who loves Christ and trusts Him, even in the midst of trial, even without seeing Him. So love your unseen Savior. Trust Him though you do not see Him now. And ask the Spirit to fill you with this joy unspeakable and full of glory, the joy of faith, the joy that anticipates glory, the joy that no circumstance can take away because it rests on the Christ you love and believe, though you have not seen Him. This joy is yours, friend, by the Spirit, as you love and trust your unseen Lord.`,
    prayer: `Lord Jesus, though I have not seen You, I love You; though I do not see You now, yet believing, I rejoice. Fill me with the joy unspeakable and full of glory that the Spirit produces in those who love and trust You. Help me to know a joy that does not depend on seeing You or on my circumstances, but rests on who You are and anticipates the glory to come. Rejoice my heart in You, my unseen Lord. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, cultivate the "joy of faith" by deliberately loving and trusting your unseen Savior. When circumstances are hard, rejoice not in them but in Christ, asking the Spirit to fill you with joy that does not depend on sight.`,
    reflect: `How can believers rejoice with "joy unspeakable" in a Savior they have not seen? What does it mean that this joy rests on faith in Christ rather than on sight or circumstances?`,
  },
  {
    day: 13,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "Love, Joy, and Peace",
    title: "Peace in the Holy Ghost",
    ref: "Romans 14:17",
    scripture: "For the kingdom of God is not meat and drink; but righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost.",
    walk: `Friend, we come now to the third fruit of the Spirit, peace, and Paul shows us in this verse that peace is a central feature of life in God's kingdom: *the kingdom of God is... righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost.* When Paul wants to describe what life in God's kingdom is really about, he names these three things, and notice that all three, righteousness, peace, and joy, are *in the Holy Ghost.* They are produced by the Spirit. Peace, like love and joy, is a fruit of the Spirit, a central mark of the kingdom life.

Consider the context in which Paul writes this. The believers in Rome were quarreling over secondary matters, over what foods were permissible to eat, over the observance of certain days. And Paul redirects them to what really matters: *the kingdom of God is not meat and drink; but righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost.* The kingdom is not about these external, secondary things; it is about righteousness, peace, and joy produced by the Spirit. Paul is reminding them, and us, not to let secondary matters rob us of the peace that should mark our life together in God's kingdom. The kingdom life is a life of Spirit-produced peace.

Notice that peace is set here alongside righteousness and joy, the three together describing the kingdom life. There is a beautiful logic to their order. Righteousness comes first, our right standing with God through Christ and the righteous living that flows from it. From righteousness flows peace, peace with God, peace within, and peace with others. And from peace flows joy, the gladness of a heart at peace with God and others. These three are bound together, all produced by the Spirit, all marks of the kingdom life. Where the Spirit reigns, there is righteousness, peace, and joy.

And see that this peace is *in the Holy Ghost.* It is the Spirit who produces it. This peace is not the mere absence of conflict, achieved by careful diplomacy or by avoiding all disagreement. It is a positive, Spirit-given peace, a deep tranquility and harmony that the Spirit works in our hearts and in our relationships. We cannot manufacture this peace by our own efforts any more than we can manufacture love or joy. It is a fruit of the Spirit, grown in us as we walk in Him. The peace that marks the kingdom of God is peace in the Holy Ghost, produced by the Spirit who dwells in us.

So pursue this kingdom peace, friend, and do not let secondary things rob you of it. Like the Roman believers, we can so easily get caught up in quarrels over matters that do not finally matter, letting disagreements over secondary things steal the peace that should mark our life in God's kingdom. Paul calls us higher. The kingdom is about righteousness, peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost, not about winning arguments over secondary matters. So hold fast to the peace the Spirit produces. Refuse to let lesser things disturb it. Walk in the Spirit, and let Him grow in you the deep, Spirit-given peace that marks the kingdom of God, a peace that flows from righteousness and overflows into joy. For the kingdom of God is righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You that Your kingdom is righteousness, peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost. Forgive me for letting secondary matters and needless quarrels rob me of the peace that should mark my life in Your kingdom. Help me to hold fast to the deep, Spirit-given peace that flows from righteousness and overflows into joy. Grow this kingdom peace in me by Your Spirit, and let it govern my heart and my relationships. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, identify one secondary matter or quarrel that has been robbing you of peace. Release it, refusing to let lesser things disturb the "peace... in the Holy Ghost" that marks God's kingdom, and pursue peace instead.`,
    reflect: `How do "righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost" describe what God's kingdom is really about? What secondary matters have been robbing you of the Spirit-given peace that should mark your life?`,
  },
  {
    day: 14,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "Love, Joy, and Peace",
    title: "The Bond of Peace",
    ref: "Ephesians 4:3",
    scripture: "Endeavouring to keep the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace.",
    walk: `Friend, we close this week on love, joy, and peace with a verse that shows us peace at work in the life of God's people together: *Endeavouring to keep the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace.* Here peace is described as a *bond*, something that binds believers together in unity. And we are called to *endeavour*, to make every effort, to keep this unity in the bond of peace. The peace that is a fruit of the Spirit is not only an inner tranquility, but a peace that binds us together with our brothers and sisters in Christ.

Notice first that there is a *unity of the Spirit* that we are called to keep. The Spirit Himself creates unity among believers, binding all who belong to Christ together into one body. This unity is His work; He creates it. But notice that we are called to *keep* it, to maintain and preserve and guard it. The Spirit creates the unity; we are responsible to keep it, to not destroy it through our quarrels and divisions and selfishness. And the bond that holds this unity together, Paul says, is peace. *The bond of peace.* Peace is the binding agent that keeps believers united, that holds the body of Christ together in harmony.

And see the effort this requires: *endeavouring.* The word means making every effort, being diligent, working hard at it. Keeping the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace does not happen automatically; it requires diligent effort. We must work at maintaining peace with our brothers and sisters, at preserving unity, at not letting conflict and division creep in. This is significant, friend, because it reminds us that while peace is a fruit grown by the Spirit, we have a real responsibility to cultivate and guard it. We must endeavour, make every effort, to keep the peace that binds us together. Peace among God's people is both a gift of the Spirit and a responsibility we must work to maintain.

Consider how much our relationships in the body of Christ depend on this bond of peace, friend. Where peace is broken, the unity of the Spirit is damaged, and the body suffers. Quarrels, grudges, divisions, and conflicts among believers tear at the bond of peace and grieve the Spirit who created the unity. But where believers endeavour to keep the peace, to forgive, to bear with one another, to pursue reconciliation, to refuse division, there the unity of the Spirit is preserved, and the body of Christ flourishes in harmony. The bond of peace holds us together, and it is worth every effort to maintain.

So endeavour to keep the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace, friend. In your relationships with other believers, make every effort to maintain peace. Be quick to forgive, slow to take offense, eager to reconcile, unwilling to let division creep in. Refuse to be a source of conflict in the body of Christ, and labor instead to be a peacemaker, a keeper of unity. For the peace that is a fruit of the Spirit is meant not only to fill your own heart, but to bind you together with your brothers and sisters in the bond of peace. Guard that bond, friend. Endeavour to keep it. And let the Spirit's peace hold the body of Christ together in unity, to the glory of God.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for the unity Your Spirit creates among Your people, and the bond of peace that holds it together. Help me to endeavour, to make every effort, to keep that unity, being quick to forgive, slow to take offense, and eager to reconcile. Keep me from being a source of conflict in Your body, and make me instead a peacemaker, a keeper of unity. Let Your Spirit's peace bind us together, to Your glory. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, "endeavour to keep the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace" in one relationship: be quick to forgive, slow to take offense, or take a step toward reconciliation, guarding the peace that binds believers together.`,
    reflect: `How is peace a "bond" that holds believers together in unity? Where do you need to "endeavour", make real effort, to keep the unity of the Spirit in the bond of peace in your relationships?`,
  },
  {
    day: 15,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "Longsuffering, Gentleness, and Goodness",
    title: "Longsuffering",
    ref: "2 Peter 3:9",
    scripture: "The Lord is not slack concerning his promise, as some men count slackness; but is longsuffering to us-ward, not willing that any should perish, but that all should come to repentance.",
    walk: `Friend, this week we take up the fruit of the Spirit that flows outward toward others, and we begin with longsuffering, that beautiful old word for patience, especially patience with people. And Peter shows us the supreme example of longsuffering: God Himself. *The Lord is... longsuffering to us-ward, not willing that any should perish.* Before we are called to be longsuffering with others, we behold the longsuffering of God toward us. And His patience with us is the model and the motive for our patience with others.

Consider what longsuffering means. It is, quite literally, suffering long, bearing patiently over a long period, especially bearing patiently with people, with their faults, their failures, their slowness, their offenses. It is the opposite of being short-tempered, easily provoked, quick to give up on people. Longsuffering keeps on being patient, keeps on bearing with others, keeps on hoping and forgiving and enduring, even when provoked, even over a long time. It is a patience that does not run out, that suffers long without giving up.

And see how Peter displays the longsuffering of God. People were mocking, asking why the Lord had not yet returned to judge the world, treating His delay as slackness, as failure to keep His promise. But Peter explains that God's delay is not slackness; it is longsuffering. *The Lord is... longsuffering to us-ward, not willing that any should perish, but that all should come to repentance.* God's patience with a sinful world, His delay in bringing judgment, flows from His longsuffering heart, His unwillingness that any should perish, His desire that all should come to repentance. God bears long with sinners, giving them time to turn to Him, because He is longsuffering. And we ourselves are recipients of this longsuffering, for He bore patiently with us in our sin until we came to repentance.

This is the model and motive for our own longsuffering, friend. We are called to be longsuffering with others because God has been so longsuffering with us. Think of how patient God has been with you, how He bore with your sin, your slowness, your repeated failures, how He did not give up on you but waited patiently until you came to Him, and how He continues to bear patiently with you still. How then can we be impatient and short-tempered with others, quick to give up on them, when God has been so longsuffering with us? The longsuffering of God toward us melts our hearts and moves us to be longsuffering toward others.

So let the longsuffering of God toward you grow longsuffering in you toward others, friend. When others try your patience, when they fail repeatedly, when they are slow to change, when they offend you, remember how longsuffering God has been with you. And ask the Spirit to grow His fruit of longsuffering in you, that you might bear patiently with others as God has borne patiently with you. This is not a patience we manufacture by gritting our teeth; it is a fruit of the Spirit, grown in hearts that have known the longsuffering of God. So behold His patience toward you, friend, and let the Spirit make you longsuffering toward others, suffering long without giving up, just as your longsuffering God has done for you.`,
    prayer: `Lord, when I consider how longsuffering You have been with me, bearing patiently with my sin, my slowness, my repeated failures, never giving up on me, my heart is melted. How can I be impatient and short-tempered with others when You have been so patient with me? Grow Your fruit of longsuffering in me by Your Spirit, that I might bear patiently with others as You have borne with me. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when someone tries your patience, pause and remember how longsuffering God has been with you. Let His patience toward you become the motive for your patience toward them, asking the Spirit to grow longsuffering in you.`,
    reflect: `How has God been "longsuffering" toward you, bearing patiently with your failures? How might remembering His patience with you grow your patience with others who try you?`,
  },
  {
    day: 16,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "Longsuffering, Gentleness, and Goodness",
    title: "Forbearing One Another",
    ref: "Colossians 3:13",
    scripture: "Forbearing one another, and forgiving one another, if any man have a quarrel against any: even as Christ forgave you, so also do ye.",
    walk: `Friend, Paul here gives us two closely related expressions of longsuffering in our relationships: *forbearing one another, and forgiving one another.* These two, forbearance and forgiveness, are how the fruit of longsuffering shows itself in the daily friction of life with other people. And Paul grounds them both in the highest possible motive: *even as Christ forgave you, so also do ye.* We forbear and forgive others because Christ has forborne and forgiven us.

Consider first *forbearing one another.* To forbear is to put up with, to bear with, to make allowance for one another's faults and weaknesses and annoying ways. It is the patience that overlooks minor offenses, that does not make an issue of every little thing, that bears graciously with the imperfections of others. We all have faults that grate on others, and others have faults that grate on us. Forbearance is the grace that bears with these patiently, that makes allowance for one another, that chooses to overlook and endure rather than to take offense at every fault. Without forbearance, life together would be impossible, for we are all flawed people living among flawed people.

And see the second: *forgiving one another, if any man have a quarrel against any.* Beyond bearing with one another's faults, there will be times when we are genuinely wronged, when someone has a real quarrel or grievance against another. And here Paul calls us not merely to forbear but to forgive, to release the offense, to let go of the grievance, to not hold the wrong against the person. Forgiveness goes beyond forbearance; it deals with real wrongs, releasing them rather than nursing them. Both are needed in the life of God's people: forbearance for the constant friction of one another's faults, and forgiveness for the real wrongs that sometimes occur.

And see the great motive Paul gives for both: *even as Christ forgave you, so also do ye.* Here is the engine of all our forbearing and forgiving: the forgiveness we have received from Christ. Christ forgave us, fully, freely, at the cost of His own blood, all our sins, our offenses against God, our repeated failures. And in light of that vast forgiveness we have received, we are called to forgive others. How can we, who have been forgiven so much, refuse to forgive others the comparatively small wrongs they do to us? The forgiveness of Christ toward us is the measure and the motive of our forgiveness toward others. We forgive as we have been forgiven.

So forbear and forgive one another, friend, even as Christ forgave you. When others' faults grate on you, practice forbearance, bearing with them, making allowance, overlooking the small offenses rather than taking issue with every one. And when you are genuinely wronged, practice forgiveness, releasing the offense, letting go of the grievance, refusing to nurse the wrong. And in both, draw your motive from the cross, where Christ forgave you so much. The fruit of longsuffering shows itself in this daily forbearing and forgiving, and it grows in hearts that remember how much they themselves have been forgiven. So forgive as you have been forgiven, friend, and let the grace you have received flow out to others.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You have called me to forbear and forgive others, even as Christ forgave me. When others' faults grate on me, give me grace to bear with them and make allowance, overlooking small offenses. And when I am genuinely wronged, help me to forgive, releasing the grievance rather than nursing it. Remind me always how much You have forgiven me, that I might forgive others freely from a grateful heart. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, practice both forbearance and forgiveness: bear graciously with one person's grating faults rather than taking issue, and release one grievance you have been holding, forgiving "even as Christ forgave you."`,
    reflect: `What is the difference between "forbearing" one another's faults and "forgiving" real wrongs? How does remembering that "Christ forgave you" become the motive for both?`,
  },
  {
    day: 17,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "Longsuffering, Gentleness, and Goodness",
    title: "Gentle Unto All",
    ref: "2 Timothy 2:24",
    scripture: "And the servant of the Lord must not strive; but be gentle unto all men, apt to teach, patient.",
    walk: `Friend, we turn now to gentleness, another fruit of the Spirit, and Paul describes it as a defining mark of the servant of the Lord: *the servant of the Lord must not strive; but be gentle unto all men.* Gentleness is the opposite of a harsh, combative, contentious spirit. It is a Christlike kindness and tenderness in how we treat others, a gentleness toward all people, even those who oppose us. And Paul makes it not optional but essential: the servant of the Lord *must* be gentle.

Notice first what Paul says the servant of the Lord must *not* do: *must not strive.* To strive here means to quarrel, to be contentious, to fight, to be combative. The servant of the Lord is not to be a quarrelsome, contentious person, always ready for a fight, always pushing and combative. This is a strong word, friend, and a needed one. There is something in our flesh that loves to strive, to argue, to win, to fight our corner, to be contentious. But Paul says the servant of the Lord must not be like this. The contentious, quarrelsome spirit is contrary to the gentleness that should mark those who serve the Lord.

And see what the servant of the Lord must be instead: *gentle unto all men, apt to teach, patient.* Gentle. Not harsh, not combative, not contentious, but gentle, treating others with kindness, tenderness, and grace. And notice the scope: gentle *unto all men.* Not just gentle to those who are gentle with us, not just to our friends and those who agree with us, but gentle to all, even to those who oppose us, even to those who are difficult. This is a Christlike gentleness, the gentleness of the One who was meek and lowly in heart, who did not break the bruised reed or quench the smoking flax, who was gentle even with His enemies.

Consider why gentleness matters so much for the servant of the Lord, friend. Paul is speaking here in the context of dealing with those who oppose the truth, those who need to be corrected and taught. And his counsel is striking: even with opponents, even with those who are wrong and need correcting, the servant of the Lord must be gentle, not striving and combative. For a harsh, contentious spirit drives people away and dishonors Christ, while a gentle spirit draws people and reflects the heart of the Savior. The way we treat others, especially those who oppose or disagree with us, either commends or contradicts the gospel we proclaim. And gentleness commends it.

So put away the striving, contentious spirit, friend, and let the Spirit grow gentleness in you. In a world that is harsh and combative, that loves to argue and fight and win, be different. Be gentle, even with those who oppose you, even in disagreement, even when correcting error. Let your manner be marked by the kindness and tenderness of Christ rather than the harshness of the flesh. This gentleness is a fruit of the Spirit, grown in us as we walk in Him and behold the gentleness of our Savior. So ask the Spirit to make you gentle unto all, friend, that you might serve the Lord not with a striving, combative spirit, but with the gentle heart of Christ.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me, as Your servant, not to strive but to be gentle unto all. Put away from me the contentious, combative spirit that loves to argue and win, and grow in me instead the gentleness of Christ. Help me to be gentle even with those who oppose me, even in disagreement, treating all people with the kindness and tenderness of my Savior. Make me gentle unto all, that my manner might commend Your gospel. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, especially in a disagreement or with someone difficult, deliberately choose gentleness over a striving, combative spirit. Treat them with the kindness and tenderness of Christ, being "gentle unto all men."`,
    reflect: `Where does the "striving," contentious spirit show up in you, especially with those who oppose or disagree with you? What would it look like to be "gentle unto all men," even your opponents?`,
  },
  {
    day: 18,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "Longsuffering, Gentleness, and Goodness",
    title: "Gentle as a Nurse",
    ref: "1 Thessalonians 2:7",
    scripture: "But we were gentle among you, even as a nurse cherisheth her children.",
    walk: `Friend, Paul here gives us one of the most tender pictures of gentleness in all of Scripture, describing his own manner among the Thessalonians: *we were gentle among you, even as a nurse cherisheth her children.* He compares his gentleness to that of a nursing mother caring for her own children, cherishing them, nurturing them, tending them with tender love. And this beautiful image shows us the warmth and tenderness of the gentleness that is a fruit of the Spirit.

Consider the image Paul chooses: *as a nurse cherisheth her children.* The word here pictures a nursing mother, and the word *cherisheth* means to warm, to nurture, to care for tenderly, as a mother warms and feeds and tends her little ones. There is no harshness here, no impatience, no roughness, but the gentlest, most tender care imaginable. A nursing mother handles her infant with infinite gentleness, patient with its weakness, tender in every touch, nurturing it with self-giving love. And this, Paul says, is how he was among the Thessalonians, and it is a picture of the gentleness the Spirit grows in us.

Notice that this gentleness is not weakness, friend. Paul was a bold apostle, courageous in the face of opposition, strong in his convictions, willing to confront error and endure great hardship. And yet, among those he served, he was gentle as a nursing mother. True gentleness is not the absence of strength; it is strength under control, power exercised with tenderness, a strong person choosing to be gentle. The nursing mother is strong, but she handles her infant with the utmost gentleness. So the servant of the Lord may be strong and bold, yet gentle in dealing with others, especially the weak, the young in faith, the struggling, the hurting.

And see the heart behind this gentleness: it cherishes. The gentle person does not merely tolerate others; they cherish them, care for them tenderly, nurture them with genuine love. Paul's gentleness flowed from love, from a heart that cherished the Thessalonians as a mother cherishes her children. This is the kind of gentleness the Spirit grows in us, a gentleness rooted in love, that handles others tenderly because it genuinely cares for them, that nurtures the weak and the struggling with cherishing love. It is not a cold, detached politeness, but a warm, tender, loving gentleness that cherishes those it cares for.

So let the Spirit grow this cherishing gentleness in you, friend, especially toward the weak and the struggling. Think of those in your life who are young in faith, or hurting, or weak, or in need of tender care. And handle them as a nursing mother handles her child, with gentleness, patience, tenderness, and cherishing love. Do not be harsh or impatient with the weak; be gentle as a nurse with her children. This tender gentleness reflects the heart of Christ, the Good Shepherd who gently carries the lambs and leads those who are with young. Ask the Spirit to make you gentle in this way, friend, cherishing others with the tender, nurturing love of a mother, that you might care for the weak and the struggling as Christ cares for you.`,
    prayer: `Lord, teach me the tender gentleness Paul showed, gentle as a nursing mother cherishing her children. Help me to handle others, especially the weak and the struggling and the young in faith, with patience, tenderness, and cherishing love, not with harshness or impatience. Let my gentleness flow from a heart that genuinely cares, reflecting the tender heart of Christ the Good Shepherd. Make me gentle and cherishing, by Your Spirit. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, show tender, "cherishing" gentleness to someone who is weak, hurting, or young in faith. Handle them as a nursing mother handles her child, with patience and nurturing love rather than harshness or impatience.`,
    reflect: `How is the gentleness of "a nurse" cherishing her children a picture of strength under control rather than weakness? Who in your life needs to be handled with this tender, cherishing gentleness?`,
  },
  {
    day: 19,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "Longsuffering, Gentleness, and Goodness",
    title: "Do Good Unto All",
    ref: "Galatians 6:10",
    scripture: "As we have therefore opportunity, let us do good unto all men, especially unto them who are of the household of faith.",
    walk: `Friend, we turn now to goodness, another fruit of the Spirit, and Paul gives it a wonderfully practical expression: *let us do good unto all men.* Goodness is not merely an inner quality but an active doing of good to others. And Paul urges us to seize every opportunity to do it: *as we have therefore opportunity, let us do good unto all men, especially unto them who are of the household of faith.* The fruit of goodness shows itself in actively doing good to others as we have opportunity.

Notice first that goodness is active. Paul does not say merely *be good*, but *do good.* Goodness, as a fruit of the Spirit, is not just an inner state of being a good person; it expresses itself in action, in actively doing good to others, in deeds of kindness, generosity, helpfulness, and service. The good person does good. They look for ways to bless others, to meet needs, to serve, to help, to be a means of blessing in the lives of those around them. The fruit of goodness is seen not in good intentions or a good reputation, but in good deeds done to real people.

And see the call to seize opportunities: *as we have therefore opportunity, let us do good.* Opportunities to do good come to us constantly, but they are easily missed if we are not looking for them. Paul calls us to be alert to these opportunities and to seize them, to do good whenever we have the chance. The day is full of opportunities to do good, to speak an encouraging word, to lend a helping hand, to meet a need, to show kindness, to serve. But these opportunities pass quickly, and if we are not intentional, we let them slip by. Paul urges us to be ready, to seize the opportunities for good that come our way, to actively do good as we have occasion.

And notice the scope, and the priority, Paul gives: *unto all men, especially unto them who are of the household of faith.* We are to do good *to all*, to everyone, believers and unbelievers alike, friends and strangers, even enemies. Goodness does not limit itself to those who are easy to love or those who can repay us; it reaches out to all. And yet there is a special priority: *especially unto them who are of the household of faith*, our fellow believers, our brothers and sisters in Christ. While we do good to all, we have a particular responsibility to care for the family of God, to actively do good to our fellow believers. Goodness reaches out to all, with a special love for the household of faith.

So seize the opportunities to do good today, friend, and every day. Be alert to the chances that come your way to bless others, and do not let them slip by. Do good to all, to everyone you encounter, looking for ways to be a blessing. And give special attention to the household of faith, actively caring for your brothers and sisters in Christ. This active doing of good is the fruit of goodness, grown in us by the Spirit and expressed in deeds of kindness and service. So do not merely intend to be good, friend; do good, as you have opportunity, to all men, especially to the family of God. Let the goodness the Spirit grows in you overflow into a life full of good deeds, to the glory of God.`,
    prayer: `Lord, grow in me the fruit of goodness, that I might not merely intend good but actively do good to others. Make me alert to the opportunities You give me each day to bless others, and help me to seize them rather than letting them slip by. Help me to do good to all, and especially to care for my brothers and sisters in the household of faith. Let my life overflow with good deeds, to Your glory. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, be alert to opportunities to "do good," and seize at least one: an encouraging word, a helping hand, a met need. Do good to whoever crosses your path, and especially look for a way to bless a fellow believer.`,
    reflect: `How is goodness an active "doing" of good, not merely an inner quality? What opportunities to do good might you be missing, and how could you better seize them "as you have opportunity"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 20,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "Longsuffering, Gentleness, and Goodness",
    title: "Full of Goodness",
    ref: "Romans 15:14",
    scripture: "And I myself also am persuaded of you, my brethren, that ye also are full of goodness, filled with all knowledge, able also to admonish one another.",
    walk: `Friend, Paul here pays the Roman believers a beautiful compliment that reveals what the fruit of goodness looks like when it is mature: *ye also are full of goodness, filled with all knowledge, able also to admonish one another.* He describes them as *full of goodness*, so filled with this fruit of the Spirit that it overflowed into their care for one another. And this phrase, *full of goodness*, gives us a vision of what we are growing toward: a heart and life so full of goodness that it overflows to bless others.

Consider that phrase, *full of goodness.* It pictures goodness not as an occasional act but as a quality that fills and characterizes a person, so that they are full of it, brimming with it, marked through and through by goodness. This is the fruit of the Spirit come to maturity, when goodness is not just something we do now and then, but something that fills us, that defines us, that overflows from us naturally because we are full of it. Paul saw this in the Roman believers, and it is what the Spirit is growing in us, a fullness of goodness that overflows into a life of blessing others.

And see what this fullness of goodness enabled: *able also to admonish one another.* Because they were full of goodness, the Roman believers were able to admonish, to counsel, to instruct and gently correct one another. This is significant, friend. Admonishing others, gently correcting and counseling them, is delicate work, and it can easily go wrong if it does not flow from goodness. Correction given from a critical, harsh, or self-righteous heart wounds and divides. But correction given from a heart full of goodness, from genuine love and care for the other person, can build up and restore. It was their fullness of goodness that made the Roman believers able to admonish one another well, with love rather than harshness.

This teaches us something important about the fruit of goodness, friend. As goodness fills us, it transforms even how we handle the difficult task of correcting and counseling others. The person full of goodness can speak hard truths in love, can admonish without wounding, can correct without condemning, because their words flow from a genuinely good heart that seeks the other person's welfare. Goodness makes us safe people to receive correction from, because we are clearly for the other person, not against them. The fullness of goodness equips us to do even the hard work of admonishing one another in a way that builds up rather than tears down.

So let the Spirit fill you with goodness, friend, until you too are *full of goodness.* This is the maturity we are growing toward, a heart and life so filled with goodness that it overflows naturally into blessing others, and that transforms even the hard work of correcting and counseling into an act of love. Ask the Spirit to fill you with goodness, to make goodness not just something you occasionally do, but something that fills and characterizes you. And as you are filled with goodness, you will find yourself able to bless others, to build them up, even to admonish them in love, from a heart that is full of the good fruit of the Spirit. May it be said of you, friend, as Paul said of the Romans, that you are full of goodness.`,
    prayer: `Lord, fill me with goodness, until it is not just something I occasionally do, but something that fills and characterizes me. Let the fruit of goodness grow in me to maturity, overflowing naturally into a life of blessing others. And let my fullness of goodness transform even the hard work of correcting and counseling others, that I might admonish in love rather than harshness, building others up rather than tearing them down. Make me full of goodness, by Your Spirit. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, ask the Spirit to fill you with goodness, and let it shape how you speak to others. If you need to correct or counsel someone, do it from a heart "full of goodness," with genuine love that builds up rather than wounds.`,
    reflect: `What would it mean to be "full of goodness," so filled with it that it overflows naturally? How does a heart full of goodness transform even the difficult task of admonishing or correcting others?`,
  },
  {
    day: 21,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "Longsuffering, Gentleness, and Goodness",
    title: "Found Faithful",
    ref: "1 Corinthians 4:2",
    scripture: "Moreover it is required in stewards, that a man be found faithful.",
    walk: `Friend, we close this week with the fruit our anchor verse calls *faith*, which here carries the rich meaning of faithfulness, reliability, trustworthiness. And Paul shows us its importance with a simple but weighty statement: *it is required in stewards, that a man be found faithful.* Faithfulness is the essential quality of a good steward, and we are all stewards of what God has entrusted to us. The fruit of faithfulness is the quality of being reliable, trustworthy, dependable, faithful in all that God has given us to do.

Consider the role of a steward, for it is the context of this verse. In Paul's day, a steward was a servant entrusted with managing his master's household and goods. The steward did not own what he managed; it belonged to the master. His one essential job was to be faithful, to manage well what was entrusted to him, to be reliable and trustworthy with his master's resources. And Paul says, *it is required in stewards, that a man be found faithful.* Faithfulness is the one thing required of a steward. Not brilliance, not success measured by worldly standards, but faithfulness, being trustworthy with what has been entrusted.

And we are all stewards, friend. God has entrusted to each of us a stewardship, gifts, abilities, time, resources, relationships, opportunities, responsibilities. None of these are ultimately our own; they belong to God, who has entrusted them to us to manage for Him. And what God requires of us as His stewards is faithfulness, that we be found faithful, trustworthy, reliable in managing what He has given us. This is the fruit of faithfulness, the quality of being a good and trustworthy steward of all that God has entrusted to us.

Notice the phrase Paul uses: *be found faithful.* Faithfulness is something that is proven over time, found to be true when tested. Anyone can appear faithful for a moment, but to *be found faithful* means to be reliable consistently, to be trustworthy when tested, to prove dependable over the long haul. Faithfulness is shown not in occasional bursts of reliability but in steady, consistent trustworthiness, in being someone who can be counted on, who follows through, who keeps their word, who manages well what is entrusted to them, day in and day out. This steady reliability is the fruit of faithfulness, and it is grown in us by the Spirit.

So aim to be found faithful, friend, in all that God has entrusted to you. Be a good steward of your gifts and abilities, using them for God's purposes. Be faithful with your time, your resources, your relationships, your responsibilities. Be reliable, trustworthy, dependable, someone who can be counted on. Keep your word. Follow through. Manage well what God has given you. This faithfulness is not glamorous, and it may not earn the world's applause, but it is what God requires of His stewards, and it is precious in His sight. And one day, the faithful steward will hear the words every believer longs to hear: *Well done, thou good and faithful servant.* So ask the Spirit to grow faithfulness in you, friend, that you might be found faithful in all things, to the glory of God.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You have entrusted to me a stewardship, gifts, time, resources, relationships, and responsibilities, and what You require is that I be found faithful. Grow in me the fruit of faithfulness, that I might be a good and trustworthy steward of all You have given me. Make me reliable, dependable, someone who keeps their word and follows through. Help me to be found faithful in all things, that one day I might hear, "Well done." In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, identify one area of stewardship, a gift, a responsibility, a relationship, where God is calling you to be "found faithful." Take one concrete step to be more reliable and trustworthy in managing what He has entrusted to you.`,
    reflect: `In what areas has God made you a "steward," entrusting things to your care? What would it look like to "be found faithful", reliable and trustworthy over the long haul, in managing what He has given you?`,
  },
  {
    day: 22,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Meek and Lowly",
    ref: "Matthew 11:29",
    scripture: "Take my yoke upon you, and learn of me; for I am meek and lowly in heart: and ye shall find rest unto your souls.",
    walk: `Friend, this final week we take up the last of the fruit, meekness and temperance, and then learn to walk out the Spirit-led life that bears much fruit. And we begin with meekness, looking to the supreme example of it: Jesus Himself. *Learn of me; for I am meek and lowly in heart.* Of all the things Jesus could have said about Himself, He chose to describe His heart as meek and lowly. And He invites us to learn this meekness from Him, promising that in it we will find rest for our souls.

Consider what meekness is, for it is often misunderstood. Meekness is not weakness, not spinelessness, not being a doormat. Jesus was meek, and He was anything but weak; He was the strongest, most courageous person who ever lived. Meekness is, rather, strength under control, power held in gentleness, a humble and gentle spirit that does not assert itself harshly or demand its own way. The meek person is not weak but humble, not spineless but gentle, not a pushover but one who has the strength to be gentle and lowly in heart. Meekness is power and strength clothed in humility and gentleness.

And see that Jesus describes meekness as a matter of the *heart*: *I am meek and lowly in heart.* Meekness is not merely an outward manner but an inward disposition, a lowliness and gentleness of heart. Jesus, though He was God, though He had all power and authority, was lowly in heart, humble, gentle, not proud or self-asserting or harsh. He who was highest of all made Himself lowest of all, washing His disciples' feet, welcoming the outcast, gentle with the weak, humble before His Father. This meekness and lowliness of heart is the very character of Christ, and it is the fruit the Spirit grows in us as we learn of Him.

And notice the invitation and the promise: *learn of me... and ye shall find rest unto your souls.* Jesus invites us to learn His meekness, to take His yoke upon us, to become like Him in this lowliness of heart. And He promises that in doing so, we will find rest for our souls. There is a deep rest in meekness, friend. The proud, self-asserting heart is restless, always striving to be recognized, to have its own way, to defend itself, to come out on top. But the meek and lowly heart is at rest, free from the exhausting need to assert and defend and prove itself, content to be humble, gentle, and lowly as Jesus was. In learning Christ's meekness, we find the rest our striving souls have longed for.

So learn meekness from Jesus, friend, and find rest for your soul. Behold His meekness and lowliness of heart, how He, though Lord of all, humbled Himself and was gentle and lowly. And ask the Spirit to grow this same meekness in you, this strength under control, this humble and gentle spirit, this lowliness of heart. Let go of the proud, self-asserting striving that keeps your soul restless, and learn instead the meekness of Christ. For meekness is not weakness but Christlikeness, and in it you will find the rest your soul has been seeking. Take His yoke, learn of Him, for He is meek and lowly in heart, and you shall find rest unto your soul.`,
    prayer: `Lord Jesus, You who are Lord of all describe Your heart as meek and lowly, and You invite me to learn this meekness from You. Grow in me Your meekness, the strength under control, the humble and gentle spirit, the lowliness of heart that marked You. Free me from the proud, self-asserting striving that keeps my soul restless, and teach me Your meekness, that I might find the rest You promise. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, learn meekness from Jesus by choosing humility over self-assertion in one situation, refusing to demand your own way or defend yourself harshly. Practice the "meek and lowly" heart of Christ, and notice the rest it brings.`,
    reflect: `How is meekness "strength under control" rather than weakness? Why do you think learning Christ's "meek and lowly" heart brings "rest unto your souls"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 23,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "The Meek Shall Inherit",
    ref: "Matthew 5:5",
    scripture: "Blessed are the meek: for they shall inherit the earth.",
    walk: `Friend, in the Beatitudes, Jesus pronounces a surprising blessing on the meek: *Blessed are the meek: for they shall inherit the earth.* This runs completely against the wisdom of the world, which says that it is the strong, the aggressive, the self-asserting who get ahead and inherit the earth, while the meek get trampled and left behind. But Jesus turns this upside down. He says it is the *meek* who are blessed, and the meek who shall inherit the earth. And in this paradox lies a profound truth about the value of the meekness the Spirit grows in us.

Consider how contrary this is to the world's thinking, friend. The world honors the aggressive, the dominant, the ones who push their way to the top, who assert themselves, who demand their rights, who fight for their own advantage. The meek, by the world's reckoning, are losers, the ones too weak or too soft to claim what is theirs, destined to be passed over and trampled. And yet Jesus says the exact opposite: *Blessed are the meek: for they shall inherit the earth.* The very ones the world counts as losers are pronounced blessed by Christ, and it is they, not the aggressive, who will finally inherit the earth.

How can this be? It is because God's kingdom operates on entirely different principles than the world's. In the world, you seize what you can by force and self-assertion. But in God's kingdom, the meek inherit, because inheritance is a gift from the Father, not something seized by force. The meek do not grasp and grab and fight for their own advantage; they entrust themselves to God and receive from His hand. And God delights to give His kingdom and all its blessings to the meek, the humble, the gentle, those who do not demand but trust, who do not grasp but receive. The meek inherit the earth because the earth is the Father's to give, and He gives it to His humble children.

This blessing also points us forward to the final fulfillment, friend. While the meek often appear to lose in this present age, the day is coming when Christ returns and the meek inherit the renewed earth, the kingdom of God in its fullness. The aggressive who seized everything for themselves in this life will find they have gained nothing eternal, while the meek who entrusted themselves to God will inherit everything. The meekness that seems so costly now, that seems to leave us at a disadvantage in a world of self-assertion, will be vindicated and rewarded when the meek inherit the earth. What looks like losing now is actually the path to gaining all things in the end.

So do not despise meekness as the world does, friend, or fear that it will leave you trampled and passed over. Jesus pronounces the meek blessed, and promises that they shall inherit the earth. In a world that honors self-assertion and aggression, choose instead the meekness of Christ, the humble, gentle, trusting spirit that does not grasp for its own advantage but entrusts itself to God. You may appear to lose by the world's reckoning, but you are blessed in God's sight, and you shall inherit the earth. So let the Spirit grow meekness in you, friend, and trust that the meek, though they seem to lose now, will inherit everything in the end.`,
    prayer: `Lord, the world tells me that the aggressive and self-asserting get ahead, while the meek are trampled. But You pronounce the meek blessed, and promise that they shall inherit the earth. Help me to believe Your upside-down kingdom wisdom, and to choose the meekness of Christ even when it seems to leave me at a disadvantage. Grow meekness in me, and help me to entrust myself to You rather than grasping for my own advantage. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when you are tempted to grasp, assert yourself, or fight for your own advantage, choose meekness instead, entrusting the outcome to God. Trust Jesus' promise that "the meek shall inherit the earth."`,
    reflect: `How does Jesus' blessing on the meek overturn the world's wisdom about who gets ahead? What would it look like to trust that "the meek shall inherit the earth" rather than grasping for your own advantage?`,
  },
  {
    day: 24,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Temperate in All Things",
    ref: "1 Corinthians 9:25",
    scripture: "And every man that striveth for the mastery is temperate in all things. Now they do it to obtain a corruptible crown; but we an incorruptible.",
    walk: `Friend, we come now to the last of the fruit our anchor verse names: temperance, which means self-control. And Paul illustrates it with the image of an athlete in training: *every man that striveth for the mastery is temperate in all things.* The athlete competing for the prize exercises strict self-control, disciplining his body and his appetites in order to win. And Paul uses this to show us the place of self-control, temperance, in the Christian life. We too are running a race, and we too must be temperate, self-controlled, if we would gain the prize.

Consider the athlete Paul describes. *Every man that striveth for the mastery is temperate in all things.* The serious athlete, training to win, exercises rigorous self-control. He disciplines his diet, his sleep, his training, his whole way of life, denying himself many things that others freely enjoy, all in order to be at his best for the competition. He is temperate, self-controlled, in all things, because he is focused on the prize. This is a picture of the discipline and self-control that should mark the Christian life. We too are in a race, running for a prize, and we too must exercise self-control, temperance, in all things.

And see what temperance, or self-control, is. It is the ability to govern ourselves, to master our appetites and impulses rather than being mastered by them, to say no to ourselves when self-indulgence would harm us or hinder our race. The temperate person is not driven about by every craving and impulse, but exercises control over themselves, ruling their appetites rather than being ruled by them. This is a crucial fruit of the Spirit, for the undisciplined, self-indulgent life is a fruitless life, easily entangled and weighed down. The temperate, self-controlled life is free to run the race well.

Notice, though, the crucial difference Paul draws between the athlete's motive and ours: *they do it to obtain a corruptible crown; but we an incorruptible.* The athlete disciplines himself for a perishable prize, a wreath of leaves that withers, a moment of earthly glory that fades. But we exercise our self-control for an incorruptible crown, an eternal prize that never fades, the reward of a faithful life and the glory of the world to come. If the athlete will discipline himself so rigorously for a fading wreath, how much more should we exercise self-control for an eternal crown? Our temperance is not for a perishable prize but for an imperishable one, and that gives it infinite worth.

So exercise temperance, friend, self-control, in all things, as one running for an eternal prize. Like the athlete, be willing to discipline yourself, to deny yourself, to master your appetites and impulses rather than being mastered by them, for the sake of running your race well. Do not let self-indulgence and lack of discipline entangle you and hinder your race. But remember, too, that this self-control is a fruit of the Spirit, not merely the product of your own willpower. As you walk in the Spirit, He grows temperance in you, enabling you to govern yourself and run with discipline. So ask the Spirit to grow self-control in you, friend, that you might be temperate in all things, running your race with discipline for the incorruptible crown that awaits.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me to be temperate, self-controlled, in all things, like an athlete disciplining himself to win the prize. Grow in me the fruit of self-control, that I might master my appetites and impulses rather than being mastered by them. Keep me from the self-indulgence and lack of discipline that would entangle and hinder my race. Help me to run with discipline, by Your Spirit, for the incorruptible crown that awaits. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, exercise "temperance" in one specific area where you tend toward self-indulgence or lack of discipline. Like an athlete in training, deny yourself for the sake of running your race well, asking the Spirit to grow self-control in you.`,
    reflect: `Where do you most need "temperance", self-control, mastering your appetites rather than being mastered by them? How does running for "an incorruptible crown" rather than a perishable one give your self-discipline new meaning?`,
  },
  {
    day: 25,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Add to Your Faith Temperance",
    ref: "2 Peter 1:5–6",
    scripture: "And beside this, giving all diligence, add to your faith virtue; and to virtue knowledge; and to knowledge temperance; and to temperance patience; and to patience godliness.",
    walk: `Friend, Peter here shows us that the fruit of the Spirit, while grown by the Spirit, also calls for our diligent effort and cooperation. *Giving all diligence, add to your faith virtue; and to virtue knowledge; and to knowledge temperance.* Peter lists a beautiful progression of Christian qualities, and right in the middle stands temperance, self-control. And he tells us to *add* these qualities, *giving all diligence.* This teaches us the important truth that growing in the Spirit's fruit involves both the Spirit's work and our diligent cooperation.

Notice the call to diligence: *giving all diligence, add to your faith.* Peter does not present the growth of Christian character as something that happens automatically while we sit passively by. He calls us to give all diligence, to make every effort, to actively add these qualities to our faith. This balances something we have emphasized throughout this book, that the fruit is grown by the Spirit, not manufactured by our effort. Both are true. The fruit is the Spirit's work, but it is not produced apart from our diligent cooperation. We are to give all diligence, working together with the Spirit, actively pursuing and adding these qualities, even as we depend on Him to grow them.

And see the progression Peter describes, with temperance in the middle: *add to your faith virtue; and to virtue knowledge; and to knowledge temperance; and to temperance patience; and to patience godliness.* These qualities build upon one another, each leading to the next, growing together into a mature Christian character. Faith is the foundation, and to it we add virtue, and knowledge, and temperance, and patience, and godliness, and on Peter goes to brotherly kindness and love. It is a picture of Christian character growing and maturing, quality building upon quality, until the believer is full and fruitful. And notice that temperance, self-control, is essential in the middle of this progression, a key link in the chain of growing character.

Consider how temperance functions in this list, friend. Knowledge, the understanding of God's truth, leads to temperance, self-control, for as we know God's truth, we are enabled to govern ourselves by it. And temperance, in turn, leads to patience, for the self-controlled person is able to endure with patience. Self-control is thus a vital hinge in the development of Christian character, the discipline that translates knowledge into endurance, that enables us to live out what we know. Without temperance, knowledge remains merely theoretical and patience is impossible; with it, our character grows toward maturity and godliness.

So give all diligence to add these qualities to your faith, friend, cooperating actively with the Spirit's work. Do not sit passively, waiting for the fruit to appear without any effort on your part; nor strive in your own strength, as though it all depended on you. Rather, work together with the Spirit, giving all diligence to pursue and add these qualities, even as you depend on Him to grow them. Pursue virtue, knowledge, temperance, patience, godliness, and love, diligently, prayerfully, depending on the Spirit at every step. This is the balance of growing in the Spirit: His work and our diligence together, producing a mature and fruitful Christian character, to the glory of God.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me to give all diligence to add to my faith these qualities of Christian character, including temperance. Help me to neither sit passively waiting for fruit without effort, nor strive in my own strength as though it all depended on me. Teach me to work together with Your Spirit, diligently pursuing these qualities even as I depend on You to grow them. Build mature, fruitful character in me, by Your Spirit and my diligent cooperation. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, "give all diligence" to cooperate with the Spirit in growing one quality from Peter's list, virtue, knowledge, temperance, patience, or godliness. Take a deliberate step to pursue it, while depending on the Spirit to grow it.`,
    reflect: `How does Peter's call to "give all diligence" balance the truth that the fruit is grown by the Spirit? What does it look like to actively cooperate with the Spirit rather than sitting passively or striving in your own strength?`,
  },
  {
    day: 26,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Mortify the Flesh by the Spirit",
    ref: "Romans 8:13",
    scripture: "For if ye live after the flesh, ye shall die: but if ye through the Spirit do mortify the deeds of the body, ye shall live.",
    walk: `Friend, as we move toward walking out the Spirit-led life, Paul gives us a crucial truth about how we deal with the flesh that opposes the Spirit's fruit: *if ye through the Spirit do mortify the deeds of the body, ye shall live.* The growing of the Spirit's fruit involves not only cultivating the positive, but also putting to death the negative, the sinful deeds of the flesh. And notice how we do it: not by our own willpower alone, but *through the Spirit.* We mortify the flesh by the power of the Spirit.

Consider the word *mortify.* It means to put to death, to kill, to actively slay. Paul is using strong language here, and deliberately so. The sinful deeds of the body, the works of the flesh that oppose the fruit of the Spirit, are not merely to be managed, restrained, or trimmed back; they are to be put to death, mortified, actively slain. This is serious, decisive, ongoing work. We do not negotiate with the flesh or make peace with our sins; we put them to death. The growing of the Spirit's fruit requires this active mortifying of the flesh, this decisive dealing with the sin that opposes our growth.

But see how we are to do it: *if ye through the Spirit do mortify the deeds of the body.* We mortify the flesh *through the Spirit*, by His power, not by our own willpower alone. This is the key, friend. Many believers try to put their sins to death by sheer willpower, gritting their teeth and striving in their own strength, and they fail, because the flesh cannot conquer the flesh. But Paul shows us a better way: we mortify the deeds of the body *through the Spirit.* As we depend on the Spirit, yield to Him, and draw on His power, He enables us to put our sins to death. The mortifying is our action, but the power for it is the Spirit's. We actively put sin to death, but we do it through the Spirit, in His strength.

And see what hangs on this: *if ye live after the flesh, ye shall die: but if ye through the Spirit do mortify the deeds of the body, ye shall live.* This is no minor matter. There are two ways to live, and they lead to two destinies. To live after the flesh, to indulge it, to let it have its way, leads to death. But to mortify the flesh through the Spirit leads to life, the abundant, growing, eternal life of the Spirit. The stakes are high, friend. Our growth, our spiritual life, even our eternal destiny, is bound up with whether we live after the flesh or mortify it through the Spirit. This is why the active putting to death of sin is so essential to the Spirit-led life.

So through the Spirit, put the deeds of the flesh to death, friend. Do not make peace with your sins or merely try to manage them; mortify them, decisively, actively, ongoingly. But do not attempt this in your own strength, which is doomed to fail. Do it through the Spirit, depending on His power, yielding to Him, drawing on His strength to slay the sin that opposes His fruit. As you mortify the flesh through the Spirit, the obstacles to your growth are removed, and the fruit of the Spirit is free to flourish. This is the necessary other side of growing in the Spirit: not only cultivating the fruit, but putting to death, through the Spirit, the flesh that would choke it. So mortify the flesh, friend, through the Spirit, and you shall live.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me not merely to manage my sins, but to put them to death, to mortify the deeds of the flesh. Yet I cannot do this in my own strength, for the flesh cannot conquer the flesh. Teach me to mortify my sins through Your Spirit, depending on His power, yielding to Him, drawing on His strength to slay what opposes Your fruit. Remove the obstacles to my growth, that Your fruit might flourish. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, identify one "deed of the flesh" that opposes the Spirit's fruit in you, and "mortify" it, not by willpower alone, but through the Spirit. Depend on His power to put it to death rather than merely managing it.`,
    reflect: `What is the difference between merely "managing" a sin and "mortifying" it, putting it to death? Why must this be done "through the Spirit" rather than by your own willpower alone?`,
  },
  {
    day: 27,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Bear Much Fruit",
    ref: "John 15:8",
    scripture: "Herein is my Father glorified, that ye bear much fruit; so shall ye be my disciples.",
    walk: `Friend, as we near the end of our journey, Jesus shows us the great purpose of all the fruit we have been pursuing: the glory of God. *Herein is my Father glorified, that ye bear much fruit; so shall ye be my disciples.* The fruit of the Spirit is not finally about our own self-improvement; it is about glorifying God. When we bear much fruit, the Father is glorified, and we are shown to be true disciples of Jesus. This lifts our whole pursuit of the fruit to its highest purpose.

Consider the context of these words. They come from Jesus' teaching about the vine and the branches, where He says, *I am the vine, ye are the branches.* And the whole point of that teaching is that the branch bears fruit not by its own effort but by abiding in the vine, drawing its life from the vine. *He that abideth in me, and I in him, the same bringeth forth much fruit: for without me ye can do nothing.* This is the very heart of growing in the Spirit, which we have seen throughout this book: the fruit is not manufactured by our effort but grown by Christ's life in us as we abide in Him. And here Jesus tells us the purpose of all that fruit: the glory of the Father.

See the great aim: *Herein is my Father glorified, that ye bear much fruit.* The fruit of the Spirit glorifies God. When the world sees love, joy, peace, patience, gentleness, goodness, faithfulness, meekness, and self-control growing in the life of a believer, it sees something that can only come from God, and the Father is glorified. The fruit testifies to the reality and the beauty of the God who produces it. So our growth in the Spirit's fruit is not finally for our own sake, to make us feel better about ourselves or to win the approval of others, but for God's glory, that He might be honored and displayed through the fruit He grows in us.

And notice that bearing fruit is the mark of true discipleship: *so shall ye be my disciples.* The genuine disciple of Jesus is known by their fruit. Jesus said elsewhere that we know a tree by its fruit, and so it is with His followers. The one who truly abides in Christ, who is truly His disciple, bears the fruit of the Spirit, and that fruit shows them to be genuinely His. This is not to say we earn our discipleship by our fruit, but that genuine discipleship inevitably produces fruit, for the one who abides in the vine cannot help but bear the vine's fruit. To bear much fruit is to show ourselves to be true disciples of Jesus.

So let the glory of God be the great aim of all your growth, friend. Pursue the fruit of the Spirit not for your own sake, but that the Father might be glorified through you. And remember the secret of bearing much fruit: abide in Christ. Stay connected to the vine. Draw your life from Him. Walk in the Spirit, depend on Him, and let His life flow through you, for without Him you can do nothing, but abiding in Him you will bear much fruit. And as you bear much fruit, the Father will be glorified, and you will be shown to be a true disciple of Jesus. This is the highest purpose of all our growing in the Spirit: not our own glory, but the glory of God, displayed through the fruit He grows in His abiding branches.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You have shown me that the great purpose of all the fruit I pursue is the glory of God. Help me to seek the fruit of the Spirit not for my own sake, but that the Father might be glorified through me. Teach me the secret of bearing much fruit: to abide in You, the true vine, drawing my life from You, for without You I can do nothing. Let me bear much fruit, to the glory of God, and be shown to be Your true disciple. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, reorient your pursuit of growth toward its highest purpose: the glory of God. As you seek to bear fruit, do it not for your own sake but for His glory, and cultivate the secret of fruitfulness by deliberately "abiding" in Christ through prayer and His Word.`,
    reflect: `How does it lift your pursuit of the fruit to know its purpose is "that my Father is glorified"? What does it mean to "abide" in Christ as the secret of bearing "much fruit"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 28,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Changed from Glory to Glory",
    ref: "2 Corinthians 3:18",
    scripture: "But we all, with open face beholding as in a glass the glory of the Lord, are changed into the same image from glory to glory, even as by the Spirit of the Lord.",
    walk: `Friend, Paul here unveils the wonderful process by which the Spirit transforms us into the likeness of Christ, and it turns on one beautiful word: *beholding.* *We all, with open face beholding as in a glass the glory of the Lord, are changed into the same image from glory to glory, even as by the Spirit of the Lord.* As we behold the glory of the Lord, we are changed into His image, transformed by the Spirit from one degree of glory to another. This is the secret of growing in the Spirit, of becoming like Christ: we are changed by beholding Him.

Consider the principle Paul reveals: we become like what we behold. *Beholding... we are changed into the same image.* As we gaze upon the glory of the Lord, fixing our attention on Christ, contemplating His beauty and His character, we are gradually transformed into His likeness. This is a profound truth about how spiritual growth happens. We do not become like Christ mainly by striving to imitate Him through gritted-teeth effort, but by beholding Him, by fixing our gaze upon Him, by contemplating His glory, and being changed by what we behold. The Spirit uses our beholding of Christ to transform us into His image.

And see the nature of this transformation: *from glory to glory.* The change is gradual and progressive, from one degree of glory to the next, ever-increasing, growing brighter and fuller over time. We are not transformed all at once into Christ's perfect likeness; we are changed from glory to glory, step by step, degree by degree, as we continue beholding Him. This is encouraging, friend, for it means that growth in Christlikeness is a process, an ongoing transformation, not a sudden leap. We may not see ourselves becoming like Christ all at once, but as we keep beholding Him, the Spirit keeps changing us, from glory to glory, until at last we shall be fully like Him.

And notice whose work this transformation is: *even as by the Spirit of the Lord.* The changing is the work of the Spirit. We behold the glory of the Lord, and the Spirit does the transforming, changing us into Christ's image. This brings together the two truths we have woven throughout this book: our part and the Spirit's part. Our part is to behold, to fix our gaze on Christ, to contemplate His glory. The Spirit's part is to transform, to change us into His image through our beholding. We cannot transform ourselves, but we can behold Christ, and as we do, the Spirit transforms us. The fruit grows, the likeness deepens, by the Spirit, as we behold.

So fix your gaze on Christ, friend, and be transformed. If you would grow in the Spirit, if you would become like Jesus, if you would bear His fruit, then behold Him. Contemplate His glory in the Scriptures, where His character and beauty are revealed. Gaze upon Him in worship and prayer. Fix the attention of your heart upon Christ, and keep beholding Him, day by day. And as you behold, the Spirit will transform you, changing you into the same image, from glory to glory. You become like what you behold, friend, so behold the glory of the Lord, and let the Spirit change you, degree by degree, into the likeness of the Christ you gaze upon, until at last His fruit fills your life and His image is fully formed in you.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You have shown me that I am transformed into Christ's likeness not mainly by striving, but by beholding Him, and that the Spirit changes me from glory to glory as I gaze upon His glory. Teach me to fix my gaze on Christ, to contemplate His beauty in Your Word, in worship, in prayer. And as I behold Him, transform me by Your Spirit into His image, degree by degree, until His fruit fills my life. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, spend time deliberately "beholding the glory of the Lord", contemplating Christ's character and beauty in the Scriptures or in worship. Trust the Spirit to transform you through your beholding, for you become like what you behold.`,
    reflect: `How does the principle that "we become like what we behold" change your approach to growth? What would it look like to grow by "beholding" Christ rather than mainly by striving to imitate Him?`,
  },
  {
    day: 29,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Strengthened by His Spirit",
    ref: "Ephesians 3:16",
    scripture: "That he would grant you, according to the riches of his glory, to be strengthened with might by his Spirit in the inner man.",
    walk: `Friend, as our journey nears its close, Paul prays a prayer for believers that we would do well to pray for ourselves: *that he would grant you, according to the riches of his glory, to be strengthened with might by his Spirit in the inner man.* This is a prayer for inner strength, for the Spirit's might at work in our inner being. And it reminds us that the growth we have pursued throughout this book depends on the strengthening work of the Spirit within us, a strength we receive by asking, according to the riches of God's glory.

Consider what Paul prays for: that we would *be strengthened with might by his Spirit in the inner man.* The strengthening Paul desires is an inner strengthening, a fortifying of the inner being, the heart, the spirit, the hidden person within. This is where the real battle of the Christian life is fought and where the fruit of the Spirit grows: in the inner man. And Paul prays that the Spirit would strengthen us there, with might, with power, fortifying our inner being so that we might stand firm, grow strong, and bear fruit. We need this inner strengthening, friend, for without it our inner being grows weak and our fruit withers.

And see who does the strengthening: *by his Spirit.* The inner strength we need is supplied by the Holy Spirit. We cannot strengthen our own inner being by willpower; the strength comes from the Spirit, who dwells within us and fortifies us with His might. This is the same truth we have seen throughout this book: the Christian life, in all its aspects, is lived by the power of the Spirit, not by our own strength. And so even our inner strength, the fortitude to stand and grow and bear fruit, comes from the Spirit, who strengthens us with might in the inner man.

And notice the lavish measure of this strengthening: *according to the riches of his glory.* God strengthens us not out of some limited supply, but according to the riches of His glory, in proportion to His infinite, glorious resources. There is no shortage of strength in God, no danger that His supply might run low. He strengthens us according to His riches, lavishly, abundantly, with all the might of His glorious power. So however weak we feel in our inner being, however much strength we need to grow and stand and bear fruit, God has more than enough to supply, according to the riches of His glory. The strengthening we need is available in inexhaustible measure.

So pray Paul's prayer for yourself, friend, and for those you love. Ask God to strengthen you with might by His Spirit in the inner man. Do not try to grow strong in your own strength, fortifying your inner being by willpower; ask the Spirit to strengthen you, according to the riches of God's glory. As you near the end of this journey of growing in the Spirit, remember that all your growth, all your fruit, depends on this inner strengthening by the Spirit. So keep asking for it. Keep depending on the Spirit's might. And trust that God will strengthen you, according to the riches of His glory, with all the power you need to grow and stand and bear the fruit of a Spirit-led life. Be strengthened, friend, with might by His Spirit in the inner man.`,
    prayer: `Lord, I pray Paul's prayer for myself: strengthen me with might by Your Spirit in the inner man. I cannot fortify my own inner being by willpower; I need the Spirit's strengthening within me. Grant it to me, according to the riches of Your glory, lavishly and abundantly, that I might stand firm, grow strong, and bear the fruit of a Spirit-led life. I depend on Your Spirit's might, not my own strength. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, pray Paul's prayer for inner strength over yourself and someone you love: *Strengthen me with might by Your Spirit in the inner man.* Depend on the Spirit's strengthening rather than trying to be strong in your own willpower.`,
    reflect: `Where do you most need to be "strengthened with might by his Spirit in the inner man"? How does it encourage you that God strengthens you "according to the riches of his glory", lavishly and without limit?`,
  },
  {
    day: 30,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Meekness, Temperance, and the Spirit-Led Life",
    title: "Filled with the Fruits of Righteousness",
    ref: "Philippians 1:11",
    scripture: "Being filled with the fruits of righteousness, which are by Jesus Christ, unto the glory and praise of God.",
    walk: `Friend, we have come to our final day, and Paul gives us the perfect verse to crown our journey, gathering up everything we have learned into a single, glorious vision: *being filled with the fruits of righteousness, which are by Jesus Christ, unto the glory and praise of God.* Here is the goal of all our growing in the Spirit: to be filled with fruit, fruit that comes by Jesus Christ, all of it for the glory and praise of God. Let us take this beautiful verse in three parts, as we close.

First, *being filled with the fruits of righteousness.* This is the goal, that our lives would be filled, brimming, overflowing with the fruit of righteousness, the very fruit of the Spirit we have explored throughout this book. Not bearing a little fruit occasionally, but being filled with fruit, our lives so full of love, joy, peace, longsuffering, gentleness, goodness, faithfulness, meekness, and self-control that they overflow. This is what the Spirit is growing us toward: not a barren or fruitless life, not even a life of meager fruit, but a life filled with the fruits of righteousness, abundant and overflowing.

Second, *which are by Jesus Christ.* The fruit comes by Jesus Christ. It is not produced by our own effort, not manufactured by our striving, but it comes by Jesus Christ, grown by His Spirit, flowing from His life in us, the fruit of our union with Him. This has been the great theme of our journey: the fruit is not ours to manufacture but Christ's to grow in us as we abide in Him and walk in His Spirit. We are filled with the fruits of righteousness not by our own labor but by Jesus Christ, who lives in us by His Spirit and bears His fruit through us. All the fruit is His doing, by His grace, through His Spirit.

And third, the great purpose of it all: *unto the glory and praise of God.* Here is where all our growing in the Spirit finally leads, and it is the same place we saw on Day 27: the glory and praise of God. The fruit of the Spirit is not finally about us, not about our self-improvement or our reputation, but about God, that He might be glorified and praised through the fruit He grows in us. When our lives are filled with the fruits of righteousness, God is glorified, His beauty is displayed, His praise resounds. This is the highest purpose of all our growth, and the note on which our whole journey rightly ends: the glory and praise of God.

So as you close this book, friend, let this be your aim and your prayer: to be filled with the fruits of righteousness, which are by Jesus Christ, unto the glory and praise of God. You came into these thirty days, perhaps, weary of trying to manufacture spiritual fruit by your own effort. May you go out having learned the better way: to abide in Christ, to walk in the Spirit, to behold the glory of the Lord, and to let the Spirit grow His fruit in you. And may your life increasingly be filled with that fruit, all of it by Jesus Christ, all of it for the glory and praise of God. To Him be all the glory, friend, now and forever, for whatever fruit His Spirit grows in you. 🙏`,
    prayer: `Lord, this is my aim and my prayer as I close: to be filled with the fruits of righteousness, which are by Jesus Christ, unto the glory and praise of God. Thank You for teaching me, over these thirty days, the better way, not to manufacture fruit by my own effort, but to abide in Christ and walk in Your Spirit. Fill my life with Your fruit, by Jesus Christ, and let it all be for Your glory and praise. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, make Philippians 1:11 your prayer and aim going forward: ask God to fill your life with the fruits of righteousness, by Jesus Christ, and dedicate all your growth to "the glory and praise of God."`,
    reflect: `Looking back over these thirty days, how has your understanding of growing in the Spirit changed? What will it mean to keep pursuing a life "filled with the fruits of righteousness... unto the glory and praise of God"?`,
  },
];

